AB  - Trusted Execution Environments (TEEs) have become essential for securing sensitive computations across modern computing platforms. While the open RISC-V architecture offered promising opportunities for security innovation, the ecosystem had lacked a production-ready TEE framework suitable for real-world deployment. This study introduced GATOR-V, the first upstream-ready, production-grade TEE ecosystem for RISC-V. By combining hardware-enforced isolation and a standards-compliant trusted operating system architecture, GATOR-V provided a complete and reusable foundation that was successfully integrated into mainstream open-source projects. The framework was implemented and validated across multiple RISC-V platforms and demonstrated its practicality through representative use cases, including secure communication based on Transport Layer Security. Experimental evaluation confirmed that GATOR-V achieved strong security guarantees with minimal performance overhead. The full implementation was released as open source to ensure transparency, reproducibility, and community adoption. Overall, this work established a foundational step toward a unified and deployable confidential computing ecosystem for RISC-V, enabling future advancements in embedded systems, Internet of Things, and confidential computing applications.
