AB  - Spiking Neural Networks (SNNs) are energy-and performance-efficient tools that have been found to be very useful in AI applications at the edge. This paper introduces SYNtzulu, an SNN processing element designed to be used in low-cost and low-power FPGA devices for near-sensor data analysis. The system is equipped with a RISC-V subsystem responsible for controlling the input/output and setting runtime parameters, thus increasing its flexibility. We evaluated the system, which was implemented on a Lattice iCE40UP5K FPGA, in various use cases employing SNNs with accuracy comparable to the state-of-the-art. SYNtzulu dissipates a maximum power of 12.05 mW when performing SNN inference, which can be reduced to an average of just 1.45 mW through the use of dynamic power management.
