AB  - Embedded system applications of present-thy scenario consume profound energy in execution and its significant fraction is due to an intensive register-file access in the processor architecture. This paper presents a novel architecture incorporating a multi-banked register file organization and a selective replacement technique referred as selective register file cache to capture actively reused and short-lived register operands. This alleviates the load on register file while performing read and write operations. Thus, the proposed architecture achieved maximum energy saving of 68% while accessing a register file over a conventional embedded processor architecture. Subsequently, it consumes an average energy of 8.48 mu J which is 51% lesser than the energy consumption of reduced-instruction set-computer (RISC-V) baseline processor-architecture.
